{[%evp 0,34,14,14,14,14,13,14,14,5,14,0,0,-20,-19,-15,-21,-15,3,-1,1,0,-1,0,32,-19,-19,-23,15,9,33,48,54,62,69,61,55]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 d6 7. c3 (7. O-O a5 8. c3 {transposes to 7.c3}) ({Worse is} 7. Nbd2 $6 g5 8. Bg3 Nh5 9. c3 (9. Nxe5 $2 {doesn't work in view of} Nxg3 10. Bxf7+ Kf8 11. Ng6+ Kxf7 12. Nxh8+ Qxh8 13. hxg3 Qxb2 {Black has full control over the dark squares, and the f7 is relatively safe. White is positionally busted.}) 9... Qf6 {Now the d3-d4 advance is problematic, so White's k-side is under pressure.} 10. Qe2 a6 11. Bb3 Be6 $15 {White was doomed to passive defence in Zubov,A - Ganguly,S Dubai 2018}) 7... a5 8. Nbd2 (8. O-O Ba7 9. Nbd2 {will be covered in the separate Chapter.}) (8. Na3 {Russia creative GM Daniil Dubov introduced this original idea.} g5 $146 {This natural move is a novelty.} ({After} 8... Bxa3 9. bxa3 Qe7 10. O-O Nb8 11. d4 {Black eventually won in Dubov,D - Vidit,S Wijk aan Zee 2022. However, at this point, I prefer White's chances due to the strong pawns centre and bishop pair.}) 9. Bg3 Nh5 10. d4 ({After} 10. Nb5 Bb6 11. d4 Qf6 {the poor g3 makes White's setup somewhat uncomfortable.}) 10... Bxa3 11. bxa3 Nf4 12. O-O ({After} 12. Bxf4 gxf4 13. dxe5 Bg4 14. exd6 Qf6 {The activity of pieces provides Black full compensation.}) 12... Qf6 $132 {The presence of f4 is quite annoying, while its capture will offer decent Black play on the g-file.}) 8... Ba7 9. a3 ({The quiet} 9. h3 g5 10. Bg3 {Grischuk,A - Giri,A chess24.com INT 2020} {can be well met by} Bd7 $146 {A flexible move. Black keeps the possibility of castling long.} 11. Qe2 ({Too risky is} 11. O-O $6 Rg8 12. Kh1 Qe7 $36 {White's king feels very unsafe as ...g5-g4 is to follow soon.}) 11... Qe7 12. O-O-O O-O-O {A long positional struggle is ahead, but the poor g3 doesn't allow White to fight for an advantage.}) (9. Qe2 {was only seen in 1 correspondence game, but I find it natural because White is planning to castle long.} Bd7 10. O-O-O Qe7 {Black is doing the same.} 11. Bb5 {Showing an intention to attack the a5.} g5 12. Bg3 O-O-O 13. Nc4 Nh5 $132 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Darmanto,H - Akram,F ICCF email 2020} {Now the critical line seems} 14. Bxc6 $146 Bxc6 15. Nxa5 Bd7 16. Kb1 f5 {Although Black is down a pawn, the strong bishops and poor g3}) (9. Bb3 {This prophylactic move doesn't seem to pose Black serious  problems either.} g5 {I see no reason for delaying this freeing move.} ({Premature is} 9... O-O 10. h3 g5 11. Nxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 $36 {Duda,J - Praggnanandhaa,R Chess24.com INT 2022}) 10. Bg3 Bd7 {The same approach. Black develops the q-side, so his king can be potentially placed there.} 11. Qe2 Qe7 12. Nc4 O-O-O $132 {Black has reached a harmonious setup, when ...d6-d5 might follow in good redaction.}) (9. O-O {is covered in the separate Chapter.}) 9... g5 ({Black shouldn't delay ...g7-g5, as was illustrated in the following case:} 9... O-O 10. h3 g5 $6 11. Nxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 Kg7 13. Qf3 {Black's king got under strong attack in Demchenko,A - Vidit,S Chess.com INT 2022}) 10. Bg3 ({The piece sacrifice usually doesn't work when Black's king is in the centre:} 10. Nxg5 $2 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Rg8 12. h4 Qe7 $19 {, followed by ...e6 and 0-0-0.}) 10... O-O 11. O-O (11. b4 {was never tried, but it looks consistent. In this case Black can harmoniously regroup the pieces by means of} Ne7 $1 12. O-O Kg7 13. d4 Nh5 $1 {It is essential to release the pressure on e5.} 14. dxe5 Nxg3 15. hxg3 Ng6 16. exd6 Qxd6 $132 {The vulnerable g3-pawn and powerful bishops provide Black enough play for a pawn.}) 11... a4 $1 {Black reasonably takes the opportunity of preventing the nasty ..b2-b4-b5. On the other hand, it is connected with a pawn sacrifice.} (11... Nh7 {is another standard idea, but it looks less effective in this case. For instance,} 12. Kh1 Kh8 13. b4 h5 {Black's play is very consistent, but White's next move diminishes control of e5.} 14. b5 $1 Ne7 {This is Adhiban,B - Vidit,S Kolkata 2021} {White should have played:} 15. Nxg5 $1 $146 Nxg5 16. Qxh5+ Nh7 17. f4 {, obtaining a stunning attack.}) 12. Kh1 {Now the a4-pawn is hanging, as there is no ...xf2+. Also, White unblocks the f-pawn.} ({Another sensible try is} 12. Bb5 {White grabs the pawn, but it costs him wasting a few tempi.} Nh5 13. Bxa4 Nxg3 14. hxg3 h5 {The main struggle will be held on the k-side, so White's extra pawn doesn't tell for now.} 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. d4 Qf6 $44 {The powerful bishops put White's king under long-termed pressure.}) 12... Bd7 {A vital developing move.} 13. h3 Nh5 {Unblocking the f-pawn and activating the knight.} 14. Bh2 {We have been following the game Mareco,S - Arjun,K Abu Dhabi 2022} {Here I mostly like the ambitious} g4 $1 $146 {Black is building his counterplay on the g-file.} 15. hxg4 Bxg4 16. Bb5 {The a4-pawn falls, but it costs White spending few tempi.} Kh8 17. Bxa4 f5 $44 {Black has a great attacking potential that fully compensates for a pawn.} *

