{[%evp 0,32,19,31,34,19,13,17,4,11,24,7,23,-34,-30,-55,-26,-42,8,11,4,-13,-15,-7,14,-9,14,13,7,-34,7,-9,26,-25,-2]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 d6 7. c3 a5 8. O-O {This is the most common choice. The current position can also be reached with other move orders.} Ba7 9. Nbd2 ({The other possible route of knight is} 9. Na3 Qe7 10. Nc2 {, but then Black benefits from keeping the king in the centre:} g5 11. Bg3 h5 $1 {This practically forces White to weaken his king with h2-h4} 12. h4 Bg4 $1 13. Ne3 O-O-O {All Black's pieces are ready to join the attack.} 14. Qb3 ({After} 14. hxg5 Nh7 15. Bh4 Qd7 $36 {White struggles to unpin the f3.}) 14... gxh4 15. Bxh4 Rdg8 {Efendiyev,E - Manso Gil,A ICCF email 2017}) ({In case of} 9. a4 {Black manages to effectively regroup the pieces and start aggressive actions on the k-side with} g5 10. Bg3 Ne7 $1 11. Nbd2 ({Even worse is} 11. Qb3 $6 {Forcing short castle isn't a good idea because it is among Black's key ideas anyways.} O-O 12. Nbd2 Ng6 13. d4 Nh5 $17 {Abdusattorov,N - Harikrishna,P Chennai 2022}) 11... Ng6 12. d4 Nd7 $1 13. Kh1 h5 {Black too over the initiative in Alexandre Bisquert,F - Martucci,M LSS email 2018}) (9. Re1 {looks risky as it weakens f2, but White vacates f1 for his knight and prepares ..d3-d4.} O-O 10. Na3 (10. Nbd2 {transposes to the main line.}) 10... g5 11. Bg3 ({I also examined:} 11. Nxg5 {This piece sacrifice should be checked carefully every time after Black goes ...g7-g5.} hxg5 12. Bxg5 Kg7 13. Qf3 Kg6 $1 {A typical approach: the king goes forward! It turns out, that White cannot comfortably defend the bishop.} 14. Bh4 Rg8) 11... Nh7 {As usual, this move is a preparation for active measures with h7-h5.} 12. Nd2 ({After} 12. Nc2 h5 13. h4 Bg4 14. hxg5 Nxg5 $15 {White has no compensation for Black's initiative on the k-side. Volokitin,A - Rakotomaharo,F Riga 2021}) 12... Ne7 $5 $146 {This standard move is a novelty. The knight's transfer on g6 will stabilize the situation in the centre and offer Black extra active possibilities on the k-side.} ({More committing is} 12... g4 13. Nb5 Bb6 14. Bb3 {This position is still unclear, the vulnerability of b6 makes it tougher for Black from a practical point of view. eventually White won in Vachier Lagrave,M - Ding,L Shenzhen 2018}) 13. d4 Ng6 14. Nc2 (14. Nb5 Bb6 {offers White nothing.}) 14... Qf6 15. h3 Nf4 {Black has a sufficient counter-play to say the least.}) 9... O-O 10. Re1 (10. a3 g5 11. Bg3 {is covered in the previous Chapter.}) 10... g5 {There is no reason for Black to delay this move any longer.} 11. Bg3 ({As earlier,} 11. Nxg5 $2 {leads nowhere:} hxg5 12. Bxg5 Kg7 13. Qf3 Rh8 14. d4 Kg6 $17) 11... Nh7 12. Nf1 ({The other plan is} 12. h3 {White temporarily secures the f3, but it also somewhat weakens the king.} Qf6 13. d4 h5 ({Worse is} 13... exd4 $6 14. e5 dxe5 15. Nxe5 $36 {the weakening ...g7-g5 starts to tell. Petrov, M - Georgeiev, K Bulgary 2022}) 14. Bb5 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Anand,V - Radjabov,T Stavanger 2022} g4 $146 15. hxg4 hxg4 16. Nh2 ({Hardly better is} 16. Bxc6 gxf3 17. Bd5 Bg4 18. Nxf3 Ng5 $132) 16... exd4 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. cxd4 ({The aggressive} 18. e5 $6 Qh6 19. cxd4 {backfires because of} f5 $1 20. exf6 Nxf6 $15 {White suffers from poor h2 and weak f2.}) 18... Bxd4 19. Nxg4 {Finally White involves the king's knight.} Bxg4 20. Qxg4+ Qg5 {Black forces the queen's trade in favorable redaction when the d4 dominates over White's rooks.}) 12... h5 13. h4 ({The quieter} 13. h3 {is well met by} Qf6 14. Ne3 Bxe3 $1 {This might look as a concession, but liquidating the strong 3 is worth it.} 15. fxe3 ({Equally possible is} 15. Rxe3 h4 16. Bh2 g4 17. hxg4 Bxg4 $132 {Black can increase the pressure on White's king with ...h8,g8 e.t.c .Valak,A - Baciak,M ICCF email 2019}) 15... h4 16. Bf2 Qh6 $132 {White's bishops were not so effective in the closed position. Limanskis,N - Seryakov,O ICCF email 2019}) 13... g4 14. N3h2 {We have been following Carlsen,M - Dominguez Perez,L chess24.com INT 2021} ({After} 14. N3d2 Ne7 15. d4 Ng6 $15 {The h4 falls. Oomen,A - Tieken,F ICCF email 2017}) 14... Qf6 $1 $146 {The queen covers a few key squares on the k-side and attacks the h4-pawn.} 15. Ne3 Ne7 16. Qc2 Be6 $132 {A complex struggle is ahead. I like Black's chances because of superior piece coordination - after all White's h2 is stuck for a long time.} *

