{[%evp 0,36,37,26,26,4,24,15,15,15,12,11,24,24,24,24,12,-1,12,10,15,17,36,4,4,10,30,13,0,0,3,-1,-9,-4,-15,-19,-19,-25,-25]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 d6 6. b4 {A speciality of GM Baadur Jobava. White grabs space on the q-side and secures c4 for his knight. On the downside, weakening c3 might tell in the long run, especially if Black can play the freeing ...d6-d5.} Bb6 7. Nbd2 (7. Qb3 {was tried by some decent players, but i don't find it sensible - the attack on f7 shouldn't bother Black, while b3 isn;t vacant for the bishop any longer.} O-O 8. a4 ({Or} 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 $15 {White has a poor piece coordination.}) 8... a5 9. b5 Ne7 10. Bg5 Ng6 {As it usually happens, the temporary activity of White's pieces backfires.} 11. O-O h6 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. fxe3 c6 $36 {White faced certain problems because ...d6-d5 is to follow soon. Iskandarov,M - Le,Q Lichess.org INT 2021}) (7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4 {Mixing g5 with b2-b4 is hardly a good idea.} g5 9. Bg3 {This position was seen in dozens of games. In my opinion, the best way of refuting White's strategy hasn't been shown yet:} a5 $5 $146 10. b5 Ne7 11. Nbd2 Ng6 $15 {Black has excellent attacking prospects on the k-side, while White's king is stuck in the centre, and the g3 is poor.}) (7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2 Ne7 {tranposes to text.}) 7... O-O 8. Bb3 (8. O-O Ne7 9. Bb3 c6 10. Nc4 Ng6 {transposes to text.}) 8... Ne7 9. Nc4 {White manages to liquidate Black's dark-squared bishop, but it costs him delaying development.} Ng6 10. O-O ({Hardly more promising for White is} 10. a4 c6 11. Nxb6 axb6 12. Be3 d5 13. Bc2 {This position took place in Onischuk,V - Buckels,V Dresden 2018} {Black could have initiated an active play in the centre with} Be6 $146 14. h3 Qc7 15. O-O h6 16. Re1 c5 $1 {It looks like White's bishops are passive, so White should switch to defense.}) 10... c6 {Black is ready to move the b6, so White's next move is practically forced.} 11. Nxb6 axb6 12. a4 Re8 13. Be3 ({After} 13. Re1 h6 14. Bc2 b5 {Black didn't have any problems in Jobava,B - Kamsky,G Chess.com INT 2022}) 13... Be6 14. Bc2 {The most ambitious - White aims to keep the bishop pair.} ({After} 14. Bxe6 Rxe6 15. Qc2 d5 {Black has nothing to worry about.}) 14... d5 {At his turn, Black takes the upper hand in the centre and puts some pressure on e4.} 15. h3 Qc7 {Connecting the rooks and overprotecting e5.} 16. Re1 h6 17. exd5 Nxd5 18. Bd2 Bf5 {The activity of knights and weak d3 provide Black more than sufficient compensation for White's bishop pair. Carlsen,M - Potkin,V Porto Carras 2018} *

