{[%evp 0,38,26,15,12,24,15,15,12,12,24,9,12,16,16,21,21,21,22,17,17,21,17,27,41,41,45,-20,20,6,21,-1,52,45,45,45,31,37,60,8,43]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 d6 6. b4 Bb6 7. a4 {The most common and natural move. The threat of a4-a5 forces Black to make a decision.} a5 {I see no reason for letting White to grab more space with ..a4-a5, although 7...a6 is the most common choice.} 8. b5 Ne7 {Black's knight moves towards g6.} 9. O-O O-O 10. Nbd2 ({Pinning the f6 with} 10. Bg5 {has no great effect:} Ng6 11. Nh4 ({After} 11. Nbd2 h6 12. Be3 c6 13. Ba2 d5 $15 {White has no compensation for Black's superiority in the centre. Polgar,J - Carlsen,M Mexico City 2012}) 11... Kh8 $5 {I like this prophylactic move. Black unpins the f7 and makes ...h7-h6 possible.} 12. Nd2 h6 13. Nxg6+ fxg6 14. Be3 Bxe3 15. fxe3 c6 {White's q-side pawns seem vulnerable, so Black has the better chances. Miettinen,K - Peli,G (IECG email 2006}) ({Aslo after} 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. fxe3 {the pressure along the f-file isn't so significant, and Black is able to build up a strong pawn centre:} c6 12. Nbd2 d5 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Bb3 {This was Nagare,A - Kirilov,I Nis 2019} {Here my natural new idea is} Qc7 $146 15. Rc1 e4 16. dxe4 dxe4 17. Ng5 Nf5 $36 {Black has a decent piece play. The e3 is a cause of worries.}) ({The quiet} 10. h3 {usually leads to a long strategic struggle. White secures the f3 to push d3-d4, but it doesn't offer any advantage.} Ng6 11. Re1 c6 {Moreover, Black is first to initiate play in the centre!} 12. Bb3 ({Also after} 12. bxc6 bxc6 13. Nbd2 d5 14. exd5 cxd5 15. Bb5 Qc7 {Black has nothing to worry about. Schueppel,R - Prozorovskij,V ICCF email 2015}) 12... d5 {The most energetic! Black exploits the vulnerability of f2.} 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. d4 (14. Nxe5 $2 {typically runs into} Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Bxf2+ 16. Kxf2 Qf6+ $19) 14... exd4 15. cxd4 Be6 {Black has a comfortable against the isolani. De Vito,G - Posada,C LSS email 2016}) 10... Ng6 11. Bb3 {The most challenging move for Black - c4 is now vacant for the knight, so Black's b6 is somewhat unstable.} c6 12. Nc4 ({Hardly more attractive is} 12. Ba3 Re8 13. Qc2 Nf4 14. Nc4 {This was Cruzado Duenas,C - De Oliveira,M ICCF email 2012} {Black could have seized the initiative by means of} d5 $1 15. Nxb6 (15. Ncxe5 Ng4 16. Nxg4 Bxg4 $40) 15... Qxb6 16. exd5 cxd5 17. Rae1 Qc7 $15 {The strong  e5 and d5 make White's setup rather cramped.}) 12... Bc7 13. Re1 h6 14. d4 {Without playing this move White doesn't really pretend to claim superiority} ({Too passive is} 14. Ne3 Re8 15. Rb1 d5 16. Qc2 Be6 $15 {Black took the upper hand in the centre. White's e3 feels misplaced. Smirin,I - Salomon,J Batumi 2019}) 14... Be6 15. Ba3 Bxc4 $1 (15... Re8 $2 16. b6 $1 Bb8 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Qxd8 Rxd8 19. Rad1 $16) 16. Bxc4 Re8 17. bxc6 (17. Bb3 {, as in Caruana,F - Nakamura,H Saint Louis 2016} {can be well met by} cxb5 $1 $146 18. axb5 Bb6 19. h3 Rc8 20. Rc1 Nf4 $15 {The strong a-passer and active f4 provide Black more than a sufficient compensation for White's bishop pair.}) 17... bxc6 18. Qc2 {White takes care of vulnerable e4.} Qc8 19. Nd2 Nf4 {Black has excellent counter-attacking prospects. Among the possible ideas are ...d6-d5 break and ...c8-g4. Polakovic,P - Grigoryev,V ICCF email 2019} *

