{[%evp 0,30,26,15,18,15,15,24,2,12,12,-13,17,-51,-37,-40,-13,-24,-3,-26,-31,-28,-23,-24,-30,-45,-56,-53,-52,-62,-31,-47,-34]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 d6 6. Bb3 {This is White's 2nd choice. The bishop's retreat is aimed at preventing the possible ...c6-a5. Also, in case Black plays ..c8-e6 White will be able to deviate from exchanging the bishops. On the downside, it costs White a tempo and limits active possibilities on the q-sie, as the b2 is blocked.} a5 {At his turn, Black secures a7 for the possible retreat of c5 and grabs some space on the q-side.} 7. Nbd2 (7. h3 h6 8. Nbd2 {is a transposition.}) (7. a4 {was tried a few times by Gm Sergei Tiviakov, who has an exceptional experience in this opening. Still, in my opinion it makes more sense to play a2-a4 when White's bishop stays on c4.} h6 8. O-O ({Harmless is also} 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. h3 Be6 10. O-O Re8 11. Re1 d5 $11) 8... O-O 9. Re1 Re8 {Overprotecting d5 in advance and preparing the thematic ...d6-d5.} 10. Nbd2 Be6 11. Bxe6 ({After} 11. Bc2 d5 {Black has nothing to worry about as well.}) 11... Rxe6 12. Qb3 Qd7 {Black reached a harmonious setup in Tiviakov,S - Jones,G Chartres 2022}) 7... h6 8. h3 {By making this move White shows his intention to play ..g2-g4 in some cases. Therefore, I find it sensible to keep the king in the centre for a while.} ({The immediate knight's transfer on g3 takes a long time and allows Black to play ..d6-d5} 8. Nf1 O-O 9. Ng3 Be6 10. O-O Bxb3 11. axb3 d5 $11 {Mamedov,R - Shankland,S Batumi 2018}) 8... Be6 {The most flexible continuation.} 9. Ba4 {A tricky move. Since the c6 is pinned, the potential ..d3-d4 break might be dangerous for Black, especially when the bishop is on e6.} ({As earlier,} 9. Nf1 {feels slow and meets} d5 $1 10. Qe2 a4 11. Bc2 d4 $1 {Black grabs more and more space.} 12. a3 b5 13. g4 Nd7 $15 {White had no compensation for his crumped pieces on the q-side. Flermoen,P - Lund,G Norway 2021}) ({I also examined} 9. Bxe6 $146 fxe6 10. Qb3 Qd7 (10... Qc8 {is possible too, but text is more ambitious.}) 11. Qxb7 Rb8 12. Qa6 d5 {The a6 is in danger, so Black has a sufficient counter-play.}) 9... O-O 10. O-O {It hardly makes sense for White to keep the king in the centre.} ({For instance,} 10. Nf1 d5 11. Qe2 {, as in Malakhov,V - Nebolsina,V Benidorm 2007} {runs into} dxe4 $1 12. dxe4 Qd6 {Connectint the rooks and overprotecting e5.} 13. Ng3 Ne7 $1 {This is the point of Black's previous play! The knight will be perfectly placed on g6.} 14. O-O Ng6 {Black doesn't have any problems. Moreover, White still has to solve the problem of passive c1.}) 10... Qb8 $1 {A clever idea. Black makes b7-b5 possible, while the queen might be potentially placed on b6.} 11. Bxc6 ({Too artificial is} 11. Bb5 {White moves his bishop too many times!} Qa7 12. a4 Ne7 13. Bc4 Bd7 14. Nb3 Bb6 {Black has reached a harmonious setup in Savchenko,B - Svidler,P Riadh 2017}) 11... bxc6 12. Re1 {This position was reached in Wang,H - Nihal,S Douglas 2018} ({The straightforward} 12. d4 {is hardly more promising:} exd4 13. cxd4 Bb6 14. Qc2 a4 $1 {Black grabs space and makes it tougher for White to develop the q-side.} 15. Nc4 Bxc4 16. Qxc4 Nxe4 17. Qxc6 Qe8 {Black has the more comfortable play because White's bishop is still on c1 and the d4 is weak. Ramsden,J - Eelvelt,H ICCF email 2017}) {Here I suggest} 12... Qa7 $146 {Black increases the pressure on f2 and makes it tougher for White to push d3-d4.} 13. Re2 ({After} 13. Qe2 a4 14. Nf1 Rfe8 15. Ng3 Rab8 {the pressure on both a2 and b2 feels annoying.}) 13... Bb6 14. Nf1 Rfe8 15. Ng3 a4 {In this complex position Black's chances are not worse: the bishop pair and pressure along the a7-f2 diagonal compensate for some structural drawbacks.} *

