{[%evp 0,28,15,18,24,24,24,12,12,12,17,9,17,-46,-37,-19,-19,-59,-26,-31,-24,-59,-45,-37,-38,-27,-14,1,17,11,20]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 d6 6. Bb3 a5 7. O-O {This quiet way of handling the position was common decades ago, when the advance of a-pawn in various redactions wasn't explored. White retreats his bishop to avoid the possible exchange of ti with ...a5.} O-O 8. Re1 ({After} 8. h3 h6 9. Re1 Re8 {Black is putting a pressure on e4 in advance, so the d3-d4 advance doesn't seem to offer White anything special.} 10. Nbd2 ({In case of} 10. d4 Ba7 11. Bc2 {the most energetic way to claim equality is} d5 $1 {Black takes advantage of superior development - White's q-side pieces are still on their initial spots.} 12. exd5 Qxd5 13. Bb3 Qd6 14. Na3 ({Or} 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Rxe5 16. Qxd6 cxd6 17. Nxe5 dxe5 $11) 14... exd4 15. Nb5 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 {This position took place in Amin,B - Sadhwani,R Abu Dhabi 2022} {Here I suggest the simple} Qd8 $146 17. Bf4 Bb6 18. Nbxd4 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Bxd4 20. cxd4 c6 {The d5-outpost fully compensates for White's bishop pair.}) 10... Be6 11. Ba4 {The most challenging for Black. Since the c6 is pinned, potentially ..d3-d4 might be quite dangerous.} ({Harmless is} 11. Bxe6 Rxe6 12. Nf1 d5 13. Qc2 Qd7 $11 {Aravindh,C - Maghsoodloo,P Chess.com INT 2020}) ({Or} 11. Nf1 Bxb3 12. Qxb3 a4 13. Qc2 ({Of course, not} 13. Qxb7 $2 Qd7 14. Qb5 Reb8 15. Qc4 Na5 {, and White suffers material losses.}) 13... d5 14. Be3 Bf8 {White has to struggle for equality as Black has the superior pawn centre. Gokerkan,C - Esipenko,A Chess.com INT 2020}) 11... Nd7 $5 {This natural move is practically untested for some reason. Now the c6 is unpinned, so White can't immediately push d3-d4. At his turn, Black is getting ready for playing ...d6-d5.} 12. Nf1 d5 $1 13. exd5 ({After} 13. Ng3 dxe4 14. dxe4 Qf6 15. Nh5 Qe7 16. Qe2 Red8 {The middlegame position that arose offers interesting play for both sides, when Black's chances are not worse.}) 13... Bxd5 14. Ne3 Bxe3 {Black concesses his dark-squares bishop, but it yields some tempi for consolidating.} ({Of course, not} 14... Be6 $2 15. d4 exd4 16. cxd4 Bb4 17. d5 $16) 15. Bxe3 f5 16. Bb3 Nf6 {Black had an excellet piece play in Antipov,M - Niemann,H Saint Louis 2022}) 8... h6 9. Nbd2 Be6 {As usual, Black doesn't mind neutralizing the powerful b3.} 10. Ba4 {This is traditionally White's main attempt to fight for the initiative.} ({There are few quieter alternatives at White's disposal:} 10. Nf1 Bxb3 11. Qxb3 a4 12. Qc2 d5 13. Be3 d4 14. cxd4 Bxd4 $11 {Black didn't face any problems in Pierron,P - Bontems,C ICCF email 2020}) (10. Bc2 $2 {is bad in view of} Ng4 11. Re2 Bxf2+ 12. Rxf2 Ne3 13. Qe2 Nxc2 14. Rb1 Bxa2 $17 {Hua,M - Locham,D Mississauga 2018}) (10. h3 Bxb3 11. axb3 Re8 {Everything is ready for thematic ...d6-d5.} 12. Nf1 d5 13. Qe2 Qd7 14. Nh4 Rad8 15. Qf3 {We have been following Kramnik,V - So,W Paris 2018} {Now Black could have exploited the vulnerability of White's q-side pawns with} Qe6 $146 16. Nf5 Bf8 17. g4 dxe4 18. dxe4 Nd7 $15) 10... Qb8 $1 {A decent positional move. Black's queen is going to be transferred on a7 or b6. Also, it is possible to grab space with ...b7-b5.} 11. Nf1 (11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. d4 Bb6 {is fine for Black because} 13. dxe5 $6 Ng4 14. Rf1 Nxe5 {put White in trouble.}) 11... b5 {The most consistent. Black grabs some space and avoids the nasty pin.} 12. Bc2 Qb6 {Connecting the rooks and attacking f2.} 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Nxe3 Ne7 {Black has reached a harmonious setup with decent prospects on the q-side. Blees,A - Buckels,V Netherlands 2018} *

