{[%evp 0,34,15,12,12,12,12,12,17,17,17,10,17,-19,-19,3,11,-28,-25,-38,15,15,-39,-20,8,30,11,9,-13,1,4,8,42,56,44,44,34]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 d6 6. Nbd2 a5 {Since our repertoire is mostly based on this advance, I see no reason for rejecting it in this redaction. In most cases, after White plays 0-0 we have transpositions to the main paths.} 7. Nf1 (7. h3 O-O 8. Nf1 {transposes to 7.f1}) 7... O-O 8. Ng3 ({In case of} 8. Bg5 Be6 9. Bb3 {Black can step out of pin with} Bxb3 10. axb3 Qe7 11. Ng3 Qe6 12. O-O h6 13. Bh4 {This was Tsydypov,Z - Bykov,E St Petersburg 2017} {Here I suggest the natural} Bb6 $146 14. Nf5 Kh7 15. Nd2 g6 $132 {The pressure against Black's king has been released, so there are no problems.}) ({The quiet} 8. a4 {is traditionally well met by} Be6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Ng3 Qd7 {Connectint the rooks and preparing ...d6-d5.} 11. O-O h6 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. fxe3 d5 $11 {Tanenbaum,Z - Svane,R Chess.com INT 2022}) (8. h3 {By making this move, White sometimes intends to start aggressive actions on the k-side with ...g2-g4.} d5 $5 {I like this ambitious response. Black takes advantage of superior development to initiate play in the centre.} 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Ng3 Nb6 11. Bb3 a4 {Depriving the bishop of the most attractive diagonal.} 12. Bc2 f5 13. O-O {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Li,R - Yang,K Philadelphia 2017} {Here I mostly like} Bd6 $146 14. Re1 h6 {Black secures his pawns centre and restricts White's minor pieces.} 15. b4 axb3 16. Bxb3+ Kh8 $132 {This position offers interesting play for both sides.}) 8... Be6 9. Bb5 {The most ambitious move.This position was recently seen in Carlsen,M - So,W Zagreb 2022} (9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 {, as in Wan,Y - Viani,A Vlissingen 2018} {should be met by} Bxc4 $1 $146 11. dxc4 g6 $1 {Not fearing of ghosts! White is unable to exploit this weakening move.} 12. h3 Kg7 13. Qe2 Qe8 {Black successfully avoids the pin and obtains an excellent position.}) {Here I suggest the following new idea:} 9... d5 $146 {At the moment, Black's pieces are better mobilized. Therefore, I find this break well-timed, although it is connected with a pawn sacrifice.} 10. Bxc6 ({After} 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 ({Dubious is} 11. Bh4 $2 g5 12. Nxg5 hxg5 13. Bxg5 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Be7 $17) 11... Qxf6 12. O-O Rfd8 13. Qa4 Bg4 $132 {The active piece play proves Black has sufficient counter-play.}) ({Harmless is} 10. O-O dxe4 11. dxe4 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Rfd8 $11) 10... bxc6 11. Nxe5 ({Worse is} 11. O-O $6 dxe4 12. dxe4 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Ng4 $36 {Black takes the upper hand.}) 11... dxe4 12. d4 Bd6 13. O-O ({In case of} 13. Nxc6 Qe8 14. Ne5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Ng4 16. Bf4 f6 {The active piece play offers  Black compensation, to say the least.}) 13... c5 {Getting rid of weak pawn.} 14. Bg5 ({Equally good is} 14. Qe2 cxd4 15. cxd4 c5 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Re8 $44) 14... cxd4 15. cxd4 Bxe5 {The simplest way to equalize.} 16. dxe5 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 Nd7 $11 {The massive exchanges lead to an equal endgame.} *

