{[%evp 0,34,12,12,12,17,17,17,17,17,17,11,17,17,59,-4,2,-30,-29,-17,13,7,16,16,12,16,6,8,12,18,22,-4,6,4,0,-1,11]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 d6 6. O-O a5 7. Re1 O-O 8. Nbd2 {By deviating from 8.h3 White is trying to save a tempo, although in some cases ...g4 might offer Black active play on the k-side.} Be6 {Our repertoire is mostly based on this} (8... Ng4 $5 9. Re2 Kh8 10. h3 Nh6 {is also worth attention and it leads to a complex double-edged struggle.}) (8... h6 {is another common way of handling the position. However, I prefer not to spend a tempo for it at this point.}) 9. a4 {A quiet choice. White is letting Black to exchange the light-squared bishops in proper redaction.} (9. b3 {The main point of this original move is to recapture with b in case Black takes on c4.} Re8 {Showing a clear intention to push ...d6-d5.} 10. Nf1 ({Harmless is} 10. Bxe6 fxe6 {Black reasonably prefers not to play xe6 in view of coming ..d3-d4.} 11. Nf1 Rf8 {The current pawn structure mostly offers Black definite counter-attacking prospects along the f-file.} (11... d5 $5 {is worth attention either.}) 12. Ng3 h6 13. a3 Qe8 14. h3 Qg6 $132 {The chances were mutual in Marbourg,D - Wharrier,J ICCF email 2020}) ({Another natural try is} 10. Bb5 Bd7 11. h3 h6 12. Bb2 {This position took place in Korn,C-Lagergren,H ICCF email 2020} (12. Nf1 {is also met by} d5 13. Ng3 Nb8 14. Bxd7 Nbxd7 {with a comfortable play.}) {Here I suggest} 12... d5 $5 $146 {This ambitious move is connected with a pawn sacrifice.} 13. exd5 {The only challenging move for Black.} Nxd5 14. Bxc6 ({After} 14. Ne4 Bf8 15. c4 Nf4 16. Bxc6 Bxc6 17. Nxe5 Nxd3 $1 {Black regains the pawn and obtains a decent posiiton.}) 14... Bxc6 15. Nxe5 Nf4 $44 {The activity of all the pieces provides Black excellent play for a pawn.}) 10... d5 {A well-timed break.} 11. exd5 Bxd5 12. Bg5 Bxc4 13. dxc4 e4 {The active c5 and pawns majority on the k-side provides Black an excellent play. Vachier Lagrave,M - Nakamura,H Chess.com INT 2018}) ({The straightforward way of handling the position is} 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Nf1 {White unblocks the d-file to push d3-d4.} a4 {A clever idea. Black grabs some space on the q-side.} 11. h3 {We have been following the game Svidler,P - Cheparinov,I Krasnaya Polyana 2021} ({After} 11. d4 Bb6 12. Ng3 Qe8 13. h3 Nh5 {Black has enough play due to pressure on White's centre. Khubukshanov,E - Lobanov,S Cheliabinsk 2020}) {Here I like the following standard idea:} 11... Nh5 $146 {The knight's transfer on f4 is especially effective when h2-h3 is played.} 12. Be3 ({Equally good is} 12. d4 Bb6 13. Be3 Qf6 $132) 12... Bxe3 13. Nxe3 Nf4 $132 {The active piece play fully compensates for slight structural drawbacks.}) ({By choosing the quiet} 9. Bb3 {White definitely cannot pretend to claim superiority} Bxb3 10. Qxb3 (10. Nxb3 h6 11. Nxc5 dxc5 12. Be3 Qd6 {was good for Black in view of weak d3. Wosch,A - Cvak,R LSS email 2020}) 10... a4 11. Qc2 Re8 12. Nf1 {This was reached Pour Agha Bala,A - Maghsoodloo,P Teheran 2019} {Here I mostly like the ambitious} d5 $146 13. Bg5 d4 14. cxd4 Bxd4 {Black has a good play because of superior pawn structure.}) 9... Bxc4 {I see no reason for delaying this.} (9... Re8 {is less precise in view of} 10. Bb5 $1 Bd7 11. Nf1 {with..d3-d4 to follow.}) 10. Nxc4 h6 {A vital move. In this redaction the potential pin of f6 could be annoying.} 11. h3 {The most common move. White prevents the possible ..g4 and makes a space for his king.} ({The immediate} 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Nxe3 Re8 {leads to the same character of play.} 13. Qb3 b6 14. Rad1 Qd7 {Both side harmoniously place their pieces. White's key idea is pushing d3-d4, so the next move is the most sensible.} 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. exd5 ({After} 16. Qxd5 Ne7 17. Qb3 Ng6 18. d4 Qg4 {Black's chances are by no means worse.}) 16... Ne7 17. d4 Ng6 18. dxe5 dxe5 $132 {The pawns majority offers Black excellent counter-attacking abilities. Mammadova,G - Pogonina,N Riga 2017}) 11... Re8 12. Be3 (12. Qb3 b6 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Nxe3 {transposes to 11.e3}) 12... Bxe3 13. Nxe3 Qd7 {Connecting the rooks and getting ready for the thematic ...d6-d5 break.} 14. Qb3 ({After} 14. Nh4 Ne7 15. Nhf5 Nxf5 16. Nxf5 Kh7 $11 {White also doesn't manage to put any pressure on Black's k-side. Hatzl,J - Susedenko,V ICCF email 2017}) 14... Ne7 15. Nh4 {was seen in Firouzja,A - Sethuraman,S Astana 2019} {Now the simplest way to neutralize White's slight activity was} b6 $146 16. Nhf5 Nxf5 17. Nxf5 d5 $11 {The f5 doesn't really bother Black.} *

