{[%evp 0,44,14,12,17,17,17,17,17,17,17,10,17,21,50,-13,-3,-28,-14,-8,-4,8,10,1,1,-23,6,21,8,6,16,2,30,27,23,23,23,42,73,12,12,12,12,3,4,9,-1]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 d6 6. O-O a5 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1 Be6 9. Bb5 {This move is by far the most popular. White deviates from exchanging the bishop, so potentially the d3-d4 advance might cause Black some difficulties because of ..d4-d5 fork.} Ba7 {Black moves his bishop in advance to meet the upcoming ..d3-d4.} ({The most common alternative is} 9... Qb8 $5 {, intending to keep control over a7-g1 diagonal.}) 10. h3 {This is an important part of White's plan that definitely involves the extension with d3-d4.} (10. Nf1 Ne7 11. d4 (11. Ng3 Ng6 12. h3 ({The benefits of possible pin along h5-d1 diagonal are illustrated in the following case:} 12. d4 c6 13. Bd3 ({The other natural retreat is} 13. Ba4 {Navara,D - Narayanan,S Germany 2022} {, and here I mostly like} Bg4 $146 {the massive attack on d4 makes it tougher for White to avoid the pin.} 14. h3 {I find this pawn sacrifice the most challenging.} ({After} 14. Be3 {Black immediately solves some space issues with} d5 $1 15. dxe5 Bxf3 16. gxf3 ({After} 16. Qxf3 Nxe5 17. Qe2 Bxe3 18. Qxe3 Nc4 {Black has nothing to worry about.}) 16... Bxe3 17. exf6 Bb6 $44 {The full control over dark squares offers Black an excellent play.}) 14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3 exd4 16. Bg5 dxc3 17. bxc3 {The pin along the h4-d8 diagonal is quite annoying for Black. Therefore, it makes sense to to give up the extra pawn with} Ne5 18. Qf5 Qc8 19. Bxf6 Qxf5 20. Nxf5 gxf6 21. Nxd6 Rfd8 {The strong tandem of e5 and a7 provides Black excellent compensation for some weaknesses.}) 13... Bg4 14. Be3 d5 $1 {This is the perfect moment for this thematic break. Black takes advantage of pinned f3 to solve the space issues.} 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Bxa7 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Rxa7 18. exd5 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Qxd5 $11 {The awkward placement of a7 is temporary, while White's pawn structure on the k-side is damaged. Vachier Lagrave,M - Rodshtein,M Mayrhofen 2022}) 12... c6 13. Ba4 d5 $1 {The most energetic. It turns out, that Black shouldn't waste time for covering his central pawn.} 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Bc2 ({Of course, not} 15. Nxe5 $2 Nxe5 16. Rxe5 Bxf2+ 17. Kxf2 Qf6+ $19) ({Premature is also} 15. d4 exd4 16. Nxd4 Qc7 $1 {White had difficulties with developing his q-side in Duda,J - Carlsen,M Wijk aan Zee 2021}) 15... Qc7 {Black reaches a harmonious setup with connected rooks.} 16. d4 exd4 17. Nxd4 Rae8 18. Bg5 Ndf4 {Black's piece coordination was preferable in Alekseenko,K - Giri,A Ekaterinburg 2020}) 11... Ng6 12. h3 (12. Ng3 {transposes to 11.g3}) 12... c6 13. Bd3 ({After} 13. Ba4 exd4 14. Nxd4 ({Or} 14. cxd4 d5 15. e5 Ne4 $132) 14... d5 15. exd5 Nxd5 {The a4 is definitely mispalced, and Black has an excellent piece play.}) 13... Nh5 14. Be3 (14. Bc2 Nhf4 15. Ng3 {transposes to the main line.}) 14... Nhf4 15. Bc2 Qc8 16. Bb3 {This position occurred in So,W - Carlsen,M chess24.com INT 2021} {Here I suggest the following continuation:} Bxh3 $1 $146 17. gxh3 a4 $1 {it is important to deprive the b3 of its diagonal.} 18. Bxa4 ({Hardly better is} 18. Bc4 b5 19. Be2 f5 $1 $40 {White's pieces are very cramped.}) 18... Qxh3 19. Bxf4 Nxf4 20. Ne3 Rae8 $36) 10... Ne7 {The knight will be well placed on g6, while Black can extend in the centre with ...c7-c6 and d6-d5.} 11. d4 (11. Nf1 {doesn't have an independent value, since} Ng6 12. Ng3 c6 13. Ba4 d5 {transposes to 10.f1}) ({Harmless is} 11. Ng5 Bd7 12. Bxd7 Qxd7 13. a4 Ng6 $11 {The g5 was definitely misplaced in Ponomariov,R - Kollars,D Dortmund 2021}) 11... Ng6 12. Ba4 ({In case of} 12. Bd3 {White takes more control over the centre, but some drawback of d3 might be claimed with} Nh5 $1 13. Nf1 (13. Nc4 Nhf4 14. Bf1 exd4 15. Nxd4 d5 16. exd5 Bxd5 $11 {Borge,N - Schandorff,L Svendborg 2022}) 13... Nhf4 14. Bc2 ({After} 14. Be3 f5 $1 15. exf5 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Bxf5 {Black develops a promising play on the k-side.}) 14... Qd7 15. Ne3 ({The careless} 15. Be3 $6 {runs into} Bxh3 $1 16. gxh3 Qxh3 17. Bxf4 Nxf4 18. Ne3 Rae8 {with a powerful attack.}) 15... exd4 16. Nxd4 ({Harmless is} 16. cxd4 d5 17. exd5 Nxd5 $11) 16... Bxd4 $1 {An excellent decision. Black concesses his strong bishop in order to diminish White's control of d5.} 17. cxd4 ({Dubious is} 17. Qxd4 $6 Rae8 18. Qd1 Nh4 $36 {Black has serious threats against White's king.}) 17... d5 18. exd5 (18. e5 $2 {meets} Nh4 $1 19. Kh2 f6 {with nearly decisive attack.}) 18... Nxd5 19. Nxd5 Bxd5 $11 {Martucci,M - Semmler,R ICCF email 2020}) 12... Nh5 13. Nf1 ({After} 13. Bc2 Nhf4 {White has nothing better than} 14. Nf1 {with a transposition.}) 13... Nhf4 14. Ng3 (14. Bc2 {transposes to 12.d3.}) 14... c6 {A useful move from few reasons: Black takes more control of d5 and prepares the possible ...b7-b5 and d6-d5. Also, c7 is now vacant for the queen.} 15. Bc2 ({I also examined} 15. Nf5 {, and then} d5 $1 {is well-timed:} 16. Nxe5 dxe4 17. Bxf4 Bxf5 18. Qh5 Be6 {offers Black a comfortable position as} 19. Rxe4 Bd5 {drops the exchange.}) 15... Qd7 {The presence of f4 around White's king is always dangerous. Black clearly shows his intention to sac on h3 or g2.} 16. Nf5 {This is practically forced - White has to block the c8-h3 diagonal.} f6 $1 17. Be3 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Dominguez Perez,L - So,W Berlin 2022} ({The careless} 17. h4 $2 {weakens the g1 and allows} d5 $1 18. Bxf4 Nxf4 19. dxe5 {This position occurred in Sjugirov,S - Hovhannisyan,R Warsaw 2021} {Now the simple} fxe5 $146 20. Nxe5 Qc7 {would have offered Black a stunning attack.}) {Here I suggest the following natural new idea:} 17... d5 $1 $146 {In my opinion, Black's pieces are well-coordinated, so this break comes on time.} 18. dxe5 (18. N3h4 {might invite major simplifications:} dxe4 19. Bxe4 exd4 20. Nxd4 ({Worse is} 20. cxd4 $6 Nxh4 21. Nxh4 Nd5 $15) 20... Nxh4 21. Bxf4 Bxd4 22. cxd4 Bf5 $11 {Black neutralizes White's strong bishop and reaches a comfortable position.}) 18... Bxe3 {Inviting interesting tactical complications.} 19. fxe3 ({After} 19. Nxe3 fxe5 20. exd5 cxd5 21. Ng5 Rad8 {the strong pawn centre makes White's position strategically dangerous.}) 19... Nxg2 $1 {An important resource. White's king is getting exposed.} 20. Kxg2 dxe4 21. Bxe4 (21. Qxd7 exf3+ 22. Kg3 Bxd7 $15) 21... Bxf5 22. Qxd7 Bxd7 {Black has the more comfortable play because of White's poor pawn structure.} *

