{[%evp 0,40,14,12,17,17,17,17,17,17,17,20,21,21,58,2,2,-17,-15,-8,8,4,-3,-35,-13,-28,-17,-18,-14,-8,-7,-7,-16,-16,-15,-17,23,21,2,-65,-57,-50,-49]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. O-O d6 6. c3 a5 7. Re1 O-O 8. h3 {The most flexible and common move. Keeping the  on its initial spot makes it possible for White to play d3-d4 faster or sometimes place it on a3. In case White still goes ..bd2 there will be a transposition to previous Chapters.} Be6 9. Bb5 {The most ambitious continuation. White reasonably prefers to keep the light-squared bishop on the board - in case of ..d3-d4 the e6 might be misplaced.} ({The complex middlegame position with double pawns on the e-file arises after} 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Be3 {White has to neutralize the strong c5 and release pressure on f2.} ({Premature is} 10. d4 Bb6 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qxd8 Raxd8 {The activity of Black's pieces overwhelms some structural drawbacks.}) 10... Bxe3 11. Rxe3 d5 {Black takes advantage of superior development to take the upper hand in the centre.} 12. Nbd2 a4 ({In case of} 12... d4 13. Re1 $1 dxc3 14. bxc3 Qxd3 15. Qb3 {White has promising compensation for a pawn.}) 13. Re2 ({After} 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Re1 Nf4 {the active play yields Black full compensation for weak e-pawns.}) 13... d4 14. Rc1 Nd7 $132 {The d4 and a4 offer Black a space advantage. Santamaria Perez,T - Jimenez Pulido,G ICCF email 2014}) ({The quiet} 9. Nbd2 {allows Black to swap bishops in comfortable redaction.} Bxc4 10. Nxc4 h6 {It makes sense to avoid the nasty pin of f6.} 11. Be3 ({Harmless is} 11. d4 exd4 12. cxd4 Bb4 {Black gains an important tempo for pushing d6-d5} 13. Bd2 d5 14. exd5 Nxd5 $11) 11... Bxe3 12. Nxe3 Re8 ({is worth attention as well.} 12... a4 $5) 13. Qb3 Qd7 14. Rad1 a4 15. Qc2 b5 {Black had no problems in Duda,J - Nakamura,H Saint Louis 2019}) 9... Ba7 10. d4 {The most challenging move for Black. White threatens 11.d5, so Black must spend a tempo to move his bishop.} ({After} 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Rxe3 Ne7 12. d4 Ng6 13. Nbd2 c6 14. Bf1 a4 $11 {Black managed to grab space on the q-side and obtained a comfortable position in Adams,M - Matlakov,M Ulcinj 2019}) (10. Nbd2 {transposes to 8.bd2}) 10... Bd7 11. Ba4 {White secures the bishop and prevents the possible tactical ideas with ...xd4. Also, it can be placed well on c2 in the long run.} ({In case of} 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 $146 ({Worse is} 12. Bxf6 $6 Qxf6 13. dxe5 Qg6 $1 {Black took the upper hand in Acs,P - Kantor,G Ajka 2021}) 12... g5 13. Bg3 Re8 {the pressure on central pawns forces White to release the tension.} 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. Nxe5 dxe5 $11 {The weak f5-spot cannot be exploited because White's pieces are not active enough.}) 11... Re8 12. Bc2 {The e4 is covered, but it is not easy for White to develop the q-side pieces because the d4 is vulnerable too.} h6 {Now White is invited to show his cards.} 13. a4 {This was played by most of the strong players. White fixes the pawn structures and secures a3 for his knight.} ({Less active is} 13. a3 b5 14. Be3 a4 15. Nbd2 Na5 $11 {Black has a comfortable play on the q-side. Melia,S - Muzychuk,M Caleta 2018}) 13... exd4 $1 {A well-timed exchange.} 14. cxd4 Nb4 {This is the point! The vulnerability of e4 makes it impossible for White to avoid the exchange of c2.} 15. Nc3 Nxc2 16. Qxc2 c6 {Vacating c7 for d8 and covering d5.} 17. Re2 {We have been following So,W - Carlsen,M chess24.com INT 2022} ({Bad is} 17. Be3 $2 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bf5 $17 {Predke,A - Harutyunian,T Abu Dhabi 2022}) {Here I suggest the following natural way of handling the position:} 17... Qc8 $5 $146 {Black vacates f5 for his bishop on advance.} 18. Bf4 d5 19. e5 (19. exd5 Nxd5 20. Nxd5 cxd5 $11) 19... Bf5 {An important intermediate move.} 20. Qb3 Ne4 $132 {The bishop pair fully compensates for White's space advantage.} *

